gland, United Kingdom":"Wethersfield, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1405–Abt 1444":"1405–about 1444","1400–1444":"1400–1444","1433–1466":"1433–1466","1405–1444":"1405–1444","1433":"1433","1466":"1466","1444":"1444","1400":"1400","1430":"1430","Abt 1444":"about 1444","1405":"1405","Wethersfield, Essex, England":"Wethersfield, Essex, England","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Wethersfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Wethersfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Amias","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from the French city of Amiens (Somme), which is recorded as  <i>Samarobriva Ambianorum</i> in classical sources.  <i>Samarobriva</i> is a Celtic place-name meaning ‘the bridge over the river Somme’, while the affix  <i>Ambianorum</i> means ‘of the Ambiani’.  <i>Ambiāni</i> is an ethnic name deriving from Celtic  <i>ambi(o)-</i> ‘around’, probably meaning ‘those on both sides (of the Somme)’ or possibly ‘the people of the world’. The affix has replaced the place-name which it once qualified, and it is the ablative form  <i>Ambiānis</i> of this ethnic name which is the source of the current place-name Amiens. For the development of the surname in England, compare ‘merchants of  <i>Amias</i>’, 1326 in   London Letter Books   E (London)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ames","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Amis</i> or from the feminine form, <i>Amice</i>. The Old French word <i>amis</i>, is from Latin <i>amicus</i> ‘friend’, which was used in Late Latin as a term for a man of the lower classes, in particular a slave. There were also derivatives of this as personal names, in particular masculine <i>Amicius</i> and feminine <i>Amicia</i>. Both were in use as personal names in England and may have contributed to the surname.","German: perhaps a nickname for an active person, from an ancient Germanic word related to Old High German <i>amazzig</i> ‘busy’.","Dutch: possibly a patronymic from <i>Ame</i> a common personal name in Holland and Friesland, an abbreviated form of an ancient Germanic personal name, perhaps beginning with <i>amel</i> ‘strong’."]},{"name":"London Letter Books","meanings":["1  English: nickname, variant of the Norman name   Petchey   (Old French  <i>peché</i>, Middle English  <i>peche</i> ‘sin’). Medieval spellings with final  <i>-e</i> can represent either  <i>peché</i> or  <i>peche</i>, so some of the earliest of the following bearers may belong with  <i>Petchey</i> rather than  <i>Petch</i>, but the two forms of the name were in any case interchangeable. Compare John Peche, tailor, 1320, identical with J. Pecchee, 1328 in   London Letter Books   E; John Peche, 1558, Moses Pechey, 1584 in   IGI   (West Hanningfield, Essex).","2  English: variant of   Spetch   with loss of initial  <i>S-</i> (unless  <i>Spetch</i> itself is a variant of  <i>Petch</i> with a prosthetic  <i>S-</i>). The two names were certainly interchangeable.   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames   notes Michael Petch or Spetch (1609–13) and Lancelot or Lance Petch or Spetch (1625–7) in the Leeds parish registers; and Benjamin Petch otherwise Spetch, 1764 in   WR Yorks Quarter Sessions   (Azerley, WR Yorks). Compare also Thome Peche, 1586, Margret Spetche, 1594 in   IGI   (Londonthorpe, Lincs); Thomas Spech, 1589, Richd. Petch, 1726 in   IGI   (Whitgift, WR Yorks)."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Amias was born in 1405, in Wethersfield, Essex, England. She married John Clench II in 1430, in Wethersfield, Essex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1444, in Wethersfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1405–Abt 1444":"1405–umbes 1444","1400–1444":"1400–1444","1433–1466":"1433–1466","1405–1444":"1405–1444","1433":"1433","1466":"1466","1444":"1444","1400":"1400","1430":"1430","Abt 1444":"umbes 1444","1405":"1405","Wethersfield, Essex, England":"Wethersfield, Essex, England","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wethersfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Wethersfield, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1405–Abt 1444":"1405–noin 1444","1400–1444":"1400–1444","1433–1466":"1433–14